{"title_page": "Yaoi Press", "text_new": "'''Yaoi Press''' is an independent [[yaoi]] [[comic]] publisher based in [[Nevada]]. Founded in 2004 by publisher [[Yamila Abraham]], the company specializes in [[Global BL]], or yaoi comics originally published outside of Asia. Yaoi Press publishes original [[OEL manga]] as well as European yaoi in translation, and features both single volume comics and comic series. As of 2020, Yaoi Press had fifty titles on the market.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/press-release/2007-01-08/yaoi-press-moves-stores-and-opens-doors|title=Yaoi Press Moves Stores and Opens Doors|publisher=[[Anime News Network]]|accessdate = 2007-07-13}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/151017.Yamila_Abraham|title=\"Yamila Abraham\"}}</ref> One of Yaoi Press's early publishing strategies in order to improve the reputation of OEL manga among yaoi fans was to headhunt famous artists of Global BL.<ref name=\"Pagliassotti Intersections\">{{cite journal|url=http://intersections.anu.edu.au/issue20/pagliassotti.htm|title=GloBLisation and Hybridisation: Publishers' Strategies for Bringing Boys' Love to the United States|last=Pagliassotti|first=Dru |authorlink=Dru Pagliassotti |date=April 2009 |issue=20|journal=Intersections: Gender and Sexuality in Asia and the Pacific}}</ref>  In October 2007, Yaoi Press launched a comic book line in order to provide a less expensive option for customers.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.icv2.com/articles/news/10450.html|title=Yaoi Launches New Comic Book Line |date=April 24, 2007|publisher=ICv2|accessdate=2009-08-07}}</ref>\n\nYaoi Press held a fan convention from the 20th to 22nd in 2008 called Yaoi Jamboree, in Phoenix, Arizona. Various manga artists who had previously worked for the company were invited as guests and an art book of submissions by attended were distributed at the convention.<ref>{{cite web|title=Yaoi Press Starts Fan Convention|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/press-release/2007-07-08/yaoi-press-starts-fan-convention}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Yaoi Jamboree 2008 Information|url=https://animecons.com/events/info/1359/yaoi-jamboree-2008}}</ref>\n\nIn late 2017, Yaoi Press launched a [[Visual novel]] spin-off of their company which produces \"Yaoi, Bara, and Otome Visual Novels\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Yaoi Press Games|url=https://ypressgames.com/}}</ref> Many reviews on [[Steam (service)]] are often mixed, which consumers criticize the weak writing and bland characters, but praise the art and concepts.<ref>{{cite url|title = Gods of Love Review||url=https://steamcommunity.com/profiles/76561198062296741/recommended/1166110/}}</ref>\n\n==Arrest==\nIn 2009, Yamila Abraham was arrested for allegedly selling a controlled over-the-counter stimulant as an herbal remedy on the now defunct PleasureHerbs.com between the years of 2005 and 2006. She was charged with seven counts of mail fraud, one count of misbranding a drug, one count of introducing goods into U.S. commerce by means of false statements, and criminal forfeiture, which she pleased not guilty. Yamila promised this would not affect her business. <ref>{{cite |title=Yaoi Press Founder Arrested for Alleged Drug Sales (Updated)|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2009-09-23/yaoi-press-founder-arrested-for-alleged-stimulant-sales}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Las Vegas woman accused of Web drug sale scheme|url=https://m.lasvegassun.com/news/2009/sep/21/las-vegas-woman-facing-fraud-charges-web-drug-sale/}}</ref>\n\n==Graphic Novels==\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n* ''Punishment''\n* ''Royal Pain''\n* ''Kingdom of Selfish Love''\n* ''Winter Demon''\n* ''Surge''\n* ''PINNED!''\n* ''Exorcisms and Pogo Sticks''\n* ''[[Yaoi Hentai]]''\n* ''[[The Aluria Chronicles]]''\n* ''Saih\u00f4shi the Guardian''\n* ''Desire of the Gods''\n* ''Spirit Marked''\n* ''Enslaved by the Dragon''\n* ''Prisoner of the Immortal''\n* ''Zesty!''\n* ''IDOL''\n* ''Wishing for the Moon''\n* ''Yaoi: An Anthology of Boys Love''\n* ''Stallion''\n* ''Treasure''\n* ''Dark Prince''\n* ''Cain''\n* ''The Lily and the Rose''\n* ''ANIMA''\n* ''Happy Yaoi Yum Yum''\n* ''Bastard King (sequel of Dark Prince)''\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Comic Books==\n* ''Yaoi Candy''\n* ''Offered to a Demon''\n\n==Art Books==\n* ''Reflections: The Artwork of KOSEN''\n* ''Dark Dreams: A Dany&Dany Yaoi Art Book''\n* ''Yaoi Gothic: An Explicit Sketchbook''\n\n==Visual Novels==\n* ''My Magical Demon Lover''\n* ''To Trust an Incubus''\n* ''Cannibal Lottery''\n* ''Morningdew Farms''\n* ''Gods of Love''\n* ''Mister Versatile''\n\n==Artists==\n* Studio K\u00f4sen\n* le Perrugine\n* M.A Sambre\n* Studio Kosaru\n* Dany&Dany\n* Yamila Abraham\n* [[Yishan Li]]\n* Laura Carboni\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.yaoipress.com  Yaoi Press'  Official Website]\n* [http://www.everythingyaoi.com  Yaoi Press'  Online Store]\n* [http://www.yaoijamboree.com  Yaoi Press'  Anime Convention]\n* Arrant, Chris (6 June 2006) [http://www.publishersweekly.com/article/CA6341172.html Home-Grown Boys' Love from Yaoi Press] ''[[Publishers Weekly]]''\n* Lees, Sharon. [http://www.akibaangels.com/articles/07_2006/yaoipress.php \"Yaoi Press: Yaoi Publishers Interviews Part 1\"]. ''Akiba Angels''. July 2006.\n* Avila, K. [http://www.katavila.com/articles/jadepages/yaoipress.pdf \"Yaoi Press: Publisher of Original English-language Yaoi\"]. ''Jade Magazine''. September 2005.\n* Beautiful Androgyny [http://www.beautifulandrogyny.com/?q=node/802 \"Interview - Yamila Abraham\"]. July, 2009.\n\n[[Category:Companies based in Paradise, Nevada]]\n[[Category:Comic book publishing companies of the United States]]\n[[Category:Visual novels]]\n", "text_old": "'''Yaoi Press''' is an independent [[yaoi]] [[comic]] publisher based in [[Nevada]]. Founded in 2004 by publisher [[Yamila Abraham]], the company specializes in [[Global BL]], or yaoi comics originally published outside of Asia. Yaoi Press publishes original [[OEL manga]] as well as European yaoi in translation, and features both single volume comics and comic series. As of 2020, Yaoi Press had fifty titles on the market.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/press-release/2007-01-08/yaoi-press-moves-stores-and-opens-doors|title=Yaoi Press Moves Stores and Opens Doors|publisher=[[Anime News Network]]|accessdate = 2007-07-13}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/151017.Yamila_Abraham|title=\"Yamila Abraham\"}}</ref> One of Yaoi Press's early publishing strategies in order to improve the reputation of OEL manga among yaoi fans was to headhunt famous artists of Global BL.<ref name=\"Pagliassotti Intersections\">{{cite journal|url=http://intersections.anu.edu.au/issue20/pagliassotti.htm|title=GloBLisation and Hybridisation: Publishers' Strategies for Bringing Boys' Love to the United States|last=Pagliassotti|first=Dru |authorlink=Dru Pagliassotti |date=April 2009 |issue=20|journal=Intersections: Gender and Sexuality in Asia and the Pacific}}</ref>  In October 2007, Yaoi Press launched a comic book line in order to provide a less expensive option for customers.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.icv2.com/articles/news/10450.html|title=Yaoi Launches New Comic Book Line |date=April 24, 2007|publisher=ICv2|accessdate=2009-08-07}}</ref>\n\nYaoi Press held a fan convention from the 20th to 22nd in 2008 called Yaoi Jamboree, in Pheonix, Arizona. Various manga artists who had previously worked for the company were invited as guests and an art book of submissions by attended were distributed at the convention.<ref>{{cite web|title=Yaoi Press Starts Fan Convention|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/press-release/2007-07-08/yaoi-press-starts-fan-convention}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Yaoi Jamboree 2008 Information|url=https://animecons.com/events/info/1359/yaoi-jamboree-2008}}</ref>\n\nIn late 2017, Yaoi Press launched a [[Visual novel]] spin-off of their company which produces \"Yaoi, Bara, and Otom